SECTION 1
What You Are Building
Plenor.ai is a company website for a professional services and advisory business. The site explains what plenor.ai is, presents its service offerings, shares insight content, and enables prospective customers to make contact. It is also the first live demonstration of the CMS-driven website approach that plenor.ai uses and sells.

The site is a CMS-operated responsive web application. All content — pages, entries, and configuration — is managed through the CMS. The front-end renders from CMS-supplied data. Developers do not manually maintain content.

The six sections of the site
Section	Purpose	Secondary navigation
Home	Curated entry point summarising the company, approach, offers, and selected insights	None
Framework	Explains the Plenor method and CMS-driven approach — not a service catalog	What Plenor Is  /  How the Approach Works  /  CMS-Driven Website Model  /  Why This Is Different
Solutions	The offer and capability area — what plenor.ai delivers to customers	Strategy and Definition  /  Website and CMS Implementation  /  Framework-Led Delivery
Insights	Articles, essays, and guides — structured knowledge content	Articles  /  Essays  /  Guides/Resources
About	Company background, founder/leadership profile, and working principles	Company  /  Founder / Leadership  /  Working Principles
Contact	Inquiry form and engagement path — single page, no secondary navigation	None

Build priority
Priority governs implementation order. Build P1 items first and do not move to P2 until P1 is complete and stable.

P1 — Build first	Home page, Framework section, Solutions section, Contact page and inquiry form, CMS content management for all content types, detail page generation from CMS entries, responsive behavior at all three breakpoints, WCAG 2.2 Level AA baseline
P2 — Build next	Insights section, About section, FAQ areas, lead capture flow, contributor role and review workflow, performance review
P3 — Later phase	Downloadable resource delivery, CRM integration, advanced analytics, marketing automation

KEY CONSTRAINT	Routine content management must work through the CMS without developer intervention.
All detail pages for Framework, Solutions, Insights, and About must be generated from CMS entries — not manually created.
CMS theme and configuration controls must resolve only to values defined in the Site Configuration Record. Free-form color, font, or spacing inputs are not permitted.

