SECTION 3
Content Types and CMS Data Model
The CMS must support the following content types. Every content type must be fully manageable through the CMS without developer intervention for routine updates. Detail pages for Framework, Solutions, Insights, and About profiles must be generated from CMS entries automatically.

Core content types
Content type	Required fields	Key notes
Site Page	title, slug, summary, body, display status, SEO title, SEO description	Landing pages and controlled standalone pages
Framework Entry	title, category, short summary, detail content, display status	Categories: What Plenor Is / How the Approach Works / CMS-Driven Website Model / Why This Is Different
Solution / Offer Entry	title, category, short summary, detail content, display status	Categories: Strategy and Definition / Website and CMS Implementation / Framework-Led Delivery
Insight Entry	title, category, short summary, detail content, author label, publish date, display status	Categories: Article / Essay / Guide/Resource
About Profile Entry	name, category, profile image, short bio, detail content, display status	Categories: Founder / Leadership / Team Member
FAQ Entry	question, answer, display status, category	May be embedded in Framework, Solutions, or Contact only
Testimonial / Proof Entry	proof type, title or source name, summary content, display status	Structurally enabled but may remain unpublished at launch
CTA / Lead Magnet Entry	title, CTA label, CTA target type, display status	Reusable blocks selectable for homepage and page sections
Inquiry Submission	name, email, inquiry type, message, submission date, workflow status	Internal admin record — not a public content type
Site Settings / Global Content	header config, footer content, logo, contact details, global CTA settings	Global shared settings for header and footer components

Content lifecycle statuses
Every public content type must support these four statuses. Draft and In Review content is never public. Only Published content appears on the site.

Draft	Being authored — not public
In Review	Awaiting approval — not public unless previewed in an approved review mode
Published	Live and public — subject to all quality and accessibility requirements
Archived	No longer primary content — must be redirected or remain intentionally accessible, not simply broken

Content relationships
These relationships must be supported in the CMS data model so that related content can be surfaced on detail pages and the homepage.

Home page	↔  featured Framework entries, featured Solution entries, featured Insight entries, featured CTA entries
Framework Entry	↔  related Solution entries, related Insight entries
Solution Entry	↔  related Insight entries
About section	↔  About Profile entries
FAQ entries	↔  relevant section pages

Homepage content fallback rules
When no items are explicitly featured through CMS selection, sections fall back using these rules in order:

Step 1	Use eligible published items in ascending orderingValue
Step 2	If orderingValue is absent, use publish date descending
Tiebreaker	Lower orderingValue wins. If tied: more recent publish date wins. If still tied: title ascending alphabetically
Empty section	Hide the section gracefully — do not render an empty layout block
Minimum per section	1 published item required for Framework, Solutions, Insights, and CTA sections to render. 1 approved published item for proof/testimonial section.

