Scheme switcher implementation
The CMS must expose a scheme selector that allows an admin to switch the active visual theme for the site. The following guidance defines exactly how this must be implemented. There is no interpretation required — the governed data model already contains all the information the selector needs.
Family boundary
For the current phase, the active Family is fixed. The plenor.ai site operates under the startup_professional Family. This is a deployment decision, not a runtime configuration decision. The CMS must not expose Family selection. Only Scheme selection is exposed, and only schemes belonging to the active Family are presented.
The three selectable schemes for plenor.ai in the current phase are: Professional Cool, Modern Technical, and Warm Professional. These are the schemes in the allowedSchemes list for the startup_professional Family with a status of Approved. No other schemes may be presented.
Dropdown construction
The CMS scheme dropdown must be constructed and behave as follows:

Step	Required behavior
Read active Family	Read currentFamily from Current Design Selection. For the current phase this will always be startup_professional.
Filter schemes	From the Scheme Records, select all schemes where parentFamily matches the active Family and status is Approved. These are the only options presented in the dropdown.
Present the dropdown	Display the filtered scheme list. The currently active scheme (read from currentScheme in Current Design Selection) should be shown as the selected value.
Write selection	Write the selected scheme identifier back to currentScheme in Current Design Selection. Trigger preset cascade resolution before committing. Do not commit the change until cascade resolution is complete.
Preset cascade resolution on scheme switch
When the admin selects a new scheme, the three active presets — typography, spacing, and radius — must each be validated against the new scheme’s allowed preset sets before the switch is committed. The rule is:
If the current preset is in the new scheme’s allowed set for that dimension, it is preserved. If it is not, it is automatically replaced by the new scheme’s default for that dimension. This resolution occurs before the new configuration is committed.
The following table shows the preset cascade behavior for a switch from Warm Professional to Professional Cool, using the current active presets as an example:

Preset dimension	Current active preset	In new scheme’s allowed set?	Resolution
Typography	tp_editorial_professional	Yes	Preserved
Spacing	sp_relaxed	Yes	Preserved
Radius	rd_soft_controlled	Yes	Preserved

NOTE	The example above shows a switch where all three presets survive because they happen to exist in both schemes’ allowed sets. This will not always be the case. If an admin switches to a scheme that does not include the current typography preset in its allowed set, that preset must be automatically replaced by the new scheme’s defaultTypographyPreset. The same applies to spacing (defaultSpacingPreset) and radius (defaultRadiusPreset). This resolution must occur before committing the switch, not after. The admin should not need to take any action; the system resolves it automatically.
The Family boundary is fixed for the current phase. Do not expose Family selection in the CMS. If the model needs to support multi-Family switching in a future phase, the configurability class on currentFamily can be changed from Fixed to Selectable in the standard at that time. No structural changes to the data model will be required.

